<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-242-017 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 348 832</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 16 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Worldtalk 400 wins award. (Touch Communications Inc.'s gateway)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Touch Communications Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Worldtalk 400 Core (Communications software) (Achievements andawards).andO;Topic:     Achievements and AwardsGateways (Interface)Software packagesData CommunicationsElectronic mail systemsX.400 Protocol.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>WORLDTALK 400 WINS AWARD 01/15/91 CAMPBELL, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1991 JAN 15(NB) -- Touch Communications' Worldtalk 400 software product, a gatewaybetwen Local Area Networks and other mail systems under the X.400 standard,was named one of the &quot;Best Products of 1990&quot; by UNIXWorld Magazine.andM;Worldtalk X.400 gateways connect the most widely used LAN messaging packagesand protocols to other systems under X.400, leaving intact the interfacesmail users are accustomed to.andP;  John Katsaros, vice president, marketing andsales for Touch said he was &quot;ecstatic&quot; about receiving the award.andM;But a Touch spokesman contacted by Newsbytes admitted that even Worldtalkisn't that easy to use.andP;  &quot;Once our product's installed, the administrator hasto be cognizant that they're sending a message out of their environment,&quot;said Chris Moore.andP;  &quot;You're faced with a broader set of names.&quot;andM;In other words, even well-engineered products like Worldtalk don't obviatethe need for an X.500 directory standard on top of X.400, so that ordinaryusers can transfer messages between mail systems.andP;  &quot;Most of our users get alocal address book, associating an X.400 name with a local alias,&quot; saidMoore.andP;  &quot;But at some point you have to correctly enter the other system'saddress correctly,&quot; a job usually left to system administrators because it'snot simple.andM;Moore also addressed an issue raised by users of the Internet system, thatits scheme could be used as the base of X.500 directories.andP;  &quot;CertainlyInternet is much shorter.andP;  But it's not more intuitive.andP;  It also lacks thestructuring aspects.andP;  That's not to say Internet doesn't work well -- itdoes.andP;  The issues driving X.400 names are administrative and organizational.andO;We could have used phone numbers.andP;  Naming is an emotional, tangible issue tomost people.&quot; The result is that while X.400 connectivity is possible, userswill have to get it through technically- proficient system administrators forsome time to come.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19910115/Press Contact: Touch Communications Denise Bowden,408/374-2500)</TEXT></DOC>